The following comments are from an off line discussion.

J. B. Rainsberger provides some insights which may be useful to all.

Basically, the question was, &quot;If you create a test method that calls an updatePassword method and sends in an argument
that should throw an IllegalArgumentException, what do you put in the catch block?&quot;


-------- Original Message --------
Subject: Re: [junit] Propagating Exceptions
Date: Tue, 26 Jun 2001 14:18:00 -0400
From: rainsber@...
To: &quot;Mike Duffy&quot; &lt;mike.duffy@...&gt;

Ask yourself: &quot;Do I need more detail than this?&quot; Maybe nothing goes in the
&quot;What goes here?&quot; spot. If you only call method X and you expect
IllegalArgumentException, then do you need more than try { X(); fail(&quot;Got
here?!&quot;); } catch (IAE success) {}?

You could check that the detail message matches or contains a certain
string, but when testing with exception classes you didn&#39;t create, you
can&#39;t always be as specific as you&#39;d like without relying too much on
details you can&#39;t control.

In your specific case, perhaps don&#39;t throw IllegalArgumentException, but
create your own subclass InvalidPasswordException. Now you have total
control.

Good luck.

