your own exceptions.

However, what if you wan to test that an IllegalArgumentException is thrown
under the proper conditions (e.g., min
password length).  If you create a test method that calls an updatePassword
method and sends in an argument that should
throw an IllegalArgumentException, what do you put in the catch block?

public void test_updatePassword() {

        try {
            instancePartnerWorker.updatePassword(&quot;abc&quot;);

            fail(&quot;The argument newPassword is less than six characters and
an IllegalArgumentException was not
thrown.&quot;);

        } catch (IllegalArgumentException e){

            // What goes here?
        }
    }



rainsber@... wrote:

&gt; Do your exceptions have any useful attributes? If not, why not?
&gt;
&gt; Consider a server that provides a number of named services. I want to
write
&gt; a test saying, &quot;If I try to invoke a non-existent service, the system
&gt; throws me an appropriate exception.&quot;
&gt;
&gt; public void testNonexistentService() {
&gt;     Server server = new Server(&quot;Some name&quot;);
&gt;     assertEquals(0, server.countServices());
&gt;
&gt;     try {
&gt;         server.invokeService(&quot;doesNotExist&quot;);
&gt;         fail(&quot;How did I invoke a nonexistent service?!&quot;);
&gt;     }
&gt;     catch (NoSuchServiceException success) {}
&gt; }
&gt;
&gt; The above test verifies that a &quot;NoSuchServiceException&quot; is thrown, but
the
&gt; exception could be more specific. Let the exception store the server and
&gt; service names so that I can check that not only was the exception thrown,
&gt; but it&#39;s indicating that &quot;doesNotExist&quot; does not exist in server &quot;Some
&gt; name&quot; and not some other service or some other server. Following is
&gt; therefore better:
&gt;
&gt; public void testNonexistentService2() {
&gt;     Server server = new Server(&quot;Some name&quot;);
&gt;     assertEquals(0, server.countServices());
&gt;
&gt;     try {
&gt;         server.invokeService(&quot;doesNotExist&quot;);
&gt;         fail(&quot;How did I invoke a nonexistent service?!&quot;);
&gt;     }
&gt;     catch (NoSuchServiceException success) {
&gt;         assertEquals(&quot;Some name&quot;, success.getServerName());
&gt;         assertEquals(&quot;doesNotExist&quot;, success.getServiceName());
&gt;     }
&gt; }
&gt;
&gt; Now I must create an exception class &quot;NoSuchServiceException&quot; that is
&gt; probably a RuntimeException and has those two attributes. I let the test
&gt; tell me how specific the exception should be.
&gt;
&gt; Get the idea?
